<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,420,1162,1189]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">
<taxonomicName box="[151,284,1162,1188]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Heteropsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ankova">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,284,1162,1188]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Ht. ankova</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sub-group
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="62.[151,1437,1233,1438]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">
Aduse-Poku 
<emphasis box="[297,361,1233,1258]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">et al.,</emphasis>
(
<number box="[376,436,1233,1258]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" value="2015.0">2015</number>
, 
<figureCitation box="[449,513,1233,1258]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1711,1733]" captionTargetBox="[166,1422,492,1675]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[150,1437,481,1690]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 1. Venation and wing patterning diagram of a fairly typical species of Heteropsis from Madagascar (Heteropis antahala group; ♂), DV. Sdbp = Supra-discocellular brush and patch. Cub = Cubital brush. Ventral banding: Cb = Costal bars. Mf = Median fleck (pale highlight). Mb = Median band. PMb = Premedian band. Ore = Ocellus ring extension. Pml = Premarginal line. Sml = Submarginal line." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/264598/files/figure.png" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">
Fig. 
<number box="[501,513,1234,1258]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
) recovered 
<taxonomicName box="[650,773,1233,1258]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Heteropsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ankova">
<emphasis box="[650,773,1233,1258]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Ht. ankova</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[829,955,1233,1258]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Heteropsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="turbata">
<emphasis box="[829,955,1233,1258]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Ht. turbata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
+ 
<taxonomicName authority="Moore, 1879" authorityName="Moore" authorityYear="1879" box="[986,1109,1233,1258]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Culapa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pallida">
<emphasis box="[986,1109,1233,1258]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Ht. pallida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
within a grade at the base of the 
<taxonomicName box="[191,320,1269,1294]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Heteropsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="strigula">
<emphasis box="[191,320,1269,1294]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Ht. strigula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group, so it is not certain that this sub-group is monophyletic, unlike the 
<taxonomicName box="[1135,1264,1269,1294]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Heteropsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="strigula">
<emphasis box="[1135,1264,1269,1294]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Ht. strigula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sub-group (see below). In 
<bibRefCitation author="Lees" box="[275,471,1305,1330]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" refString="Lees, D. C. (1997) Systematics and biogeography of Madagascan mycalesine butterflies (Lepidoptera: Satyrinae). Unpubl. PhD thesis, University of London, London, 411 pp." type="book" year="1997">
Lees (
<number box="[344,405,1306,1330]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" value="1997.0">1997</number>
: 
<number box="[416,461,1305,1330]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" value="156.0">156</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
, these ‘ 
<taxonomicName box="[557,681,1305,1330]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Heteropsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ankova">
<emphasis box="[557,681,1305,1330]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Ht. ankova</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
subgroup’ species formed a morphological clade with 
<taxonomicName box="[1304,1436,1305,1330]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Heteropsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tornado">
<emphasis box="[1304,1436,1305,1330]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Ht. tornado</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(‘FFTFR’). All these species feature expression of an ocellus in space-M 
<number box="[976,987,1342,1366]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" value="3.0">3</number>
and sometimes space-M 
<number box="[1269,1282,1342,1366]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" value="2.0">2</number>
of the 
<collectionCode box="[1362,1433,1342,1365]" country="United Kingdom" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:13236" name="Hollinwood Botanists' and Field Naturalists' Society" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">HWD</collectionCode>
. The species occur in marshy areas near rainforest margins (
<taxonomicName box="[818,943,1377,1402]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Heteropsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="turbata">
<emphasis box="[818,943,1377,1402]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Ht. turbata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Moore, 1879" authorityName="Moore" authorityYear="1879" box="[997,1118,1377,1402]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Culapa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pallida">
<emphasis box="[997,1118,1377,1402]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Ht. pallida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) or in rainforest, sometimes within metres of forest margins, always flying and perching quite low, from sealevel to over 
<quantity box="[1188,1273,1414,1438]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" unit="m" value="2000.0">2000 m</quantity>
elevation.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
